        "Power is the rate of doing work",
        "Both winches do the same amount of work",
        "Winch A completes the work in less time",
        "Power is inversely proportional to time"
      ],
      "hint": "Power is the 'speedometer' of work. Efficiency is always less than 100% because real-world machines always lose some energy as heat."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "guidedPractice": {
    "title": "Guided Practice: Winch System Calculation",
    "objective": "Calculate the work done, mechanical power output, and efficiency of a winch system using provided formulas.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Formula 1: Work (J) = Force (N) x Distance (m)",
      "Formula 2: Power Output (W) = Work (J) / Time (s)",
      "Formula 3: Efficiency (%) = (Power Output / Power Input) x 100"
    ],
    "questionText": "An electric winch pulls a cable with a force of 800 N over a distance of 20 meters. The task takes 40 seconds to complete. The motor driving the winch has an electrical power input of 500 W. Calculate: 1) The work done in Joules. 2) The mechanical power output in Watts. 3) The efficiency of the system as a percentage.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "16,000 J",
      "400 W",
      "80%"
    ],
    "hint": "Start by multiplying the force by the distance to find the Joules, then divide that by the time in seconds to find the output wattage."
  },
  "practice": {
    "title": "Independent Practice: Conveyor Motor Efficiency",
    "objective": "Independently determine the efficiency of a motor-driven system by calculating mechanical output from work and time.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Efficiency is the ratio of useful power output to the total power input.",
      "Power is the rate of doing work (Joules per second).",
      "Ensure all units are in SI (Newtons, Metres, Seconds, Watts) before finalizing your calculation."
    ],
    "questionText": "A conveyor motor moves a load with a constant force of 1,200 N over a distance of 10 meters. This movement is completed in 25 seconds. If the motor is supplied with 600 W of electrical power, what is the efficiency of the system?",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "80%"
    ],
    "hint": "First, find the total work done. Second, find the mechanical power output by dividing that work by the time. Finally, divide the output power by the 600 W input power."
  }
}

